-black and white take turns
-you can only move once in a turn
-white cannot capture it's own piece and vice versa
-a pawn may only go one space forward, unless a piece is in it's way
-a pawn may only attack one space diagonally, but cannot go diagonal if it is not attacking
-a pawn may go two spaces if it is on the starting row
-when a pawn reaches the end of the Chessboard, it turns in to a queen and then it is the next players turn
-a rook may only move horizontally and vertically
-a bishop may only move diagonally
-the king can move one space in any direction
-the queen can move horizontally and vertically and diagonal any amount of spaces
-the knight is the only piece that can jump over pieces
-the knight can move like so: one space vertically or horizontally, then two spaces vertically or horizontally and vice versa (like an L)
-a piece may not go off the Chessboard
-when the king can be taken by the other side in one move, it is called check
-if the king can be taken by the other side, and nothing can be done to stop the other side, then it is called checkmate
-a check can be blocked by another piece, the king can move to get out of chess, or the piece that is checking can be taken to prevent checkmate
-a king can castle when one of the rooks have not been moved and the king have not been moved
-castling is when the rook switches with the king when there is no piece between the king and the rook
-any of the two rooks may be used to castle
-to castle, move the king two space towards the rook, then move the rook to the other side of the king
-there may be 32 or less chess pieces on the chessboard
-white moves first
-the king may not move in to check
-a castle can be done when the king is not in check, not moving through check, and not moving in to check
-a move, called en passant is when a pawn is right next to your pawn, you can move forward one and capture the other side's pawn
-en passant is only allowed when the opponent moves 2 spaces on their first move and where the pawn goes is next to your pawn
-stalemate is when you or your opponent cannot make any moves that are allowed
-a pawn may promote to any piece it would like to
-you may only win by checkmate- that means the game is over
